(a) an operable anchor and a crewmember capable of stopping the barge from drifting ashore, (b) an emergency system that will allow the tug to retrieve the barge if the tow line breaks, and (c) any other means, equivalent to the above, to protect the barge from grounding.
In addition, the Act requires that a tug engaged in towing barges have a fire suppression system or its equivalent.
In response to the Coast Guard Authorization Act of 1996, the Coast Guard issued a notice of proposed rulemaking (NPRM) in October 1997 to improve towing-vessel and tank barge safety in a variety of areas.
The proposed rules were developed in consultation with the TSAC, as required by the Authorization Act, and were based on the recommendations made in the RRAT report.
The Coast Guard proposed the following rules in response to the Scandia accident: For improving fire suppression measures aboard towing vessels, the Coast Guard proposed that all new tugs and, within 2 years, all existing tugs have the following: Â· Â· A firemain system and fire pump that can be operated from the tug's pilothouse and locally at the pump.
